coherent set of methodologies, aligning their sociological, public policy, and political science and international relations perspectives, to account for discrepancies between official rhetoric and policy practice and actual perceptions of decline and crisis in contemporary Japan. Each chapter focuses on a distinct policy field to gauge the effectiveness and the implications of political responses through an analysis of how crises are narrated and used to justify policy interventions. Transcending boundaries between issue areas and domestic and international politics, these essays paint a dynamic picture of the contested but changing nature of social, economic, and, ultimately political institutions as they constitute the transforming Japanese state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEconomic developmentzJapany1989-. 0aNational securityzJapanxHistoryy1989-. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Japanese Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Language and Culture. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / General.2bisacsh1 aBreaden, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiavacci, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasegawa, Koichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaslow, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaslow, Sebastian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMason, Ra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’shea, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShibata, Saori, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuzuki, Shogo, econtributor.4ctb4h